[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] In mathematics, the **convergence condition by Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy** (CFL) is a necessary condition for convergence while solving certain partial differential equations (usually hyperbolic PDEs) numerically.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] It arises in the numerical analysis of explicit time integration schemes, when these are used for the numerical solution.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] As a consequence, the time step must be less than a certain upper bound, given a fixed spatial increment, in many explicit time-marching computer simulations; otherwise, the simulation produces incorrect or unstable results.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The condition is named after Richard Courant, Kurt Friedrichs, and Hans Lewy who described it in their 1928 paper.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The principle behind the condition is that, for example, if a wave is moving across a discrete spatial grid and we want to compute its amplitude at discrete time steps of equal duration, then this duration must be less than the time for the wave to travel to adjacent grid points.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] As a corollary, when the grid point separation is reduced, the upper limit for the time step also decreases.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The spatial coordinates and the time are discrete-valued independent variables, which are placed at regular distances called the *interval length* and the *time step*, respectively.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Using these names, the CFL condition relates the length of the time step to a function of the interval lengths of each spatial coordinate and of the maximum speed that information can travel in the physical space.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Operatively, the CFL condition is commonly prescribed for those terms of the finite-difference approximation of general partial differential equations that model the advection phenomenon.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The value of $C_{\max }$ changes with the method used to solve the discretised equation, especially depending on whether the method is explicit or implicit.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] If an explicit (time-marching) solver is used then typically $C_{\max }=1$ .
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] Implicit (matrix) solvers are usually less sensitive to numerical instability and so larger values of $C_{\max }$ may be tolerated.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] with the obvious meanings of the symbols involved.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The interval length is not required to be the same for each spatial variable $\Delta x_{i},i=1,\ldots ,n$ .
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] This "degree of freedom" can be used to somewhat optimize the value of the time step for a particular problem, by varying the values of the different interval to keep it not too small.
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] where ${\bf {w}}\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is a vector of arbitrary dimension N and ${\bf {\underline {A}}}\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}\times \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is accordingly a matrix of order N .
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] where $|\lambda |_{\max }$ is the magnitude of the largest eigenvalue of the matrix ${\bf {\underline {A}}}$ .
[src:finite-difference-methods/courant-friedrichs-lewy-condition] The extension to multiple dimensions follows the logic described above.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] In numerical analysis, the **Crank–Nicolson method** is a finite difference method used for numerically solving the heat equation and similar partial differential equations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] It is implicit in time, can be written as an implicit Runge–Kutta method, and it is numerically stable.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] The method was developed by John Crank and Phyllis Nicolson in the 1940s.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] For diffusion equations (and many other equations), it can be shown the Crank–Nicolson method is unconditionally stable.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] However, the approximate solutions can still contain (decaying) spurious oscillations if the ratio of time step $\Delta t$ times the thermal diffusivity to the square of space step, $\Delta x^{2}$ , is large (typically, larger than 1/2 per Von Neumann stability analysis).
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] For this reason, whenever large time steps or high spatial resolution is necessary, the less accurate backward Euler method is often used, which is both stable and immune to oscillations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] The Crank–Nicolson method is based on the trapezoidal rule, giving second-order convergence in time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] For linear equations, the trapezoidal rule is equivalent to the implicit midpoint method—the simplest example of a Gauss–Legendre implicit Runge–Kutta method—which also has the property of being a geometric integrator.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] Note that this is an *implicit method*: to get the "next" value of u in time, a system of algebraic equations must be solved.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] If the partial differential equation is nonlinear, the discretization will also be nonlinear, so that advancing in time will involve the solution of a system of nonlinear algebraic equations, though linearizations are possible.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] The Crank–Nicolson method is often applied to diffusion problems.
[src:finite-difference-methods/crank-nicolson-method] Given that the terms on the right-hand side of the equation are known, this is a tridiagonal problem, so that $u_{i}^{n+1}$ may be efficiently solved by using the tridiagonal matrix algorithm in favor over the much more costly matrix inversion.
