[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference-method] To summarize, usually the Crank–Nicolson scheme is the most accurate scheme for small time steps.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference-method] For larger time steps, the implicit scheme works better since it is less computationally demanding.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference-method] The explicit scheme is the least accurate and can be unstable, but is also the easiest to implement and the least numerically intensive.
