[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] This is often a problem because it amounts to changing the interval of discretization.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Forward differences applied to a sequence are sometimes called the binomial transform of the sequence, and have a number of interesting combinatorial properties.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Forward differences may be evaluated using the Nörlund–Rice integral.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Higher-order differences can also be used to construct better approximations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] As mentioned above, the first-order difference approximates the first-order derivative up to a term of order h.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] This can be proven by expanding the above expression in Taylor series, or by using the calculus of finite differences, explained below.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] If necessary, the finite difference can be centered about any point by mixing forward, backward, and central differences.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Sometimes, the low order derivatives of a function may be analytically known, but high order derivatives are not.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] In these cases, the high order derivatives can be approximated by finite difference of low order derivatives, which is often more accurate and numerically more stable than finite difference of the function *f* (*x*) itself.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] This is sometimes called seminumerical differentiation.
