[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Using linear algebra one can construct finite difference approximations which utilize an arbitrary number of points to the left and a (possibly different) number of points to the right of the evaluation point, for any order derivative.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] This involves solving a linear system such that the Taylor expansion of the sum of those points around the evaluation point best approximates the Taylor expansion of the desired derivative.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Such formulas can be represented graphically on a hexagonal or diamond-shaped grid.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] This is useful for differentiating a function on a grid, where, as one approaches the edge of the grid, one must sample fewer and fewer points on one side.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Finite difference approximations for non-standard (and even non-integer) stencils given an arbitrary stencil and a desired derivative order may be constructed.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] An important application of finite differences is in numerical analysis, especially in numerical differential equations, which aim at the numerical solution of ordinary and partial differential equations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] The idea is to replace the derivatives appearing in the differential equation by finite differences that approximate them.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] The resulting methods are called finite difference methods.
[src:finite-difference-methods/finite-difference] Common applications of the finite difference method are in computational science and engineering disciplines, such as thermal engineering, fluid mechanics, etc.
