[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] The **Lax–Wendroff method**, named after Peter Lax and Burton Wendroff, is a numerical method for the solution of hyperbolic partial differential equations, based on finite differences.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] It is second-order accurate in both space and time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] This method is an example of explicit time integration where the function that defines the governing equation is evaluated at the current time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] Suppose one has an equation of the following form: ${\frac {\partial u(x,t)}{\partial t}}+{\frac {\partial f(u(x,t))}{\partial x}}=0$ where x and t are independent variables, and the initial state, *u*(*x*, 0) is given.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] This linear scheme can be extended to the general non-linear case in different ways.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] To avoid the Jacobian evaluation, use a two-step procedure.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] What follows is the Richtmyer two-step Lax–Wendroff method.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] The first step in the Richtmyer two-step Lax–Wendroff method calculates values for *f*(*u*(*x*, *t*)) at half time steps, *t**n* + 1/2 and half grid points, *x**i* + 1/2.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] In the second step values at *t**n* + 1 are calculated using the data for *t**n* and *t**n* + 1/2.
[src:finite-difference-methods/lax-wendroff-method] Another method of this same type was proposed by MacCormack.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] In computational physics, the term advection scheme refers to a class of numerical discretization methods for solving hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] In the so-called upwind schemes *typically*, the so-called upstream variables are used to calculate the derivatives in a flow field.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] That is, derivatives are estimated using a set of data points biased to be more "upwind" of the query point, with respect to the direction of the flow.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] Historically, the origin of upwind methods can be traced back to the work of Courant, Isaacson, and Rees who proposed the CIR method.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] To illustrate the method, consider the following one-dimensional linear advection equation ${\frac {\partial u}{\partial t}}+a{\frac {\partial u}{\partial x}}=0$ which describes a wave propagating along the x -axis with a velocity a .
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] This equation is also a mathematical model for one-dimensional linear advection.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] Consider a typical grid point i in the domain.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] In a one-dimensional domain, there are only two directions associated with point i – left (towards negative infinity) and right (towards positive infinity).
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] If a is positive, the traveling wave solution of the equation above propagates towards the right, the left side is called the *upwind* side and the right side is the *downwind* side.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] Similarly, if a is negative the traveling wave solution propagates towards the left, the left side is called *downwind* side and right side is the *upwind* side.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] If the finite difference scheme for the spatial derivative, $\partial u/\partial x$ contains more points in the upwind side, the scheme is called an **upwind-biased** or simply an **upwind scheme**.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] The simplest upwind scheme possible is the first-order upwind scheme.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] where n refers to the t dimension and i refers to the x dimension.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] Equation (3) is a general way of writing any upwind-type schemes.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] The upwind scheme is stable if the following Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy condition (CFL) is satisfied.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] A Taylor series analysis of the upwind scheme discussed above will show that it is first-order accurate in space and time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] Modified wavenumber analysis shows that the first-order upwind scheme introduces severe numerical diffusion/dissipation in the solution where large gradients exist due to necessity of high wavenumbers to represent sharp gradients.
[src:finite-difference-methods/upwind-scheme] The spatial accuracy of the first-order upwind scheme can be improved by including 3 data points instead of just 2, which offers a more accurate finite difference stencil for the approximation of spatial derivative.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] In numerical analysis, **von Neumann stability analysis** (also known as Fourier stability analysis) is a procedure used to check the stability of finite difference schemes as applied to linear partial differential equations.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] The analysis is based on the Fourier decomposition of numerical error and was developed at Los Alamos National Laboratory after having been briefly described in a 1947 article by British researchers John Crank and Phyllis Nicolson.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] This method is an example of explicit time integration where the function that defines governing equation is evaluated at the current time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Later, the method was given a more rigorous treatment in an article co-authored by John von Neumann, wherein it is described as a "heuristic procedure" patterned after the more rigorous Courant–Friedrichs–Lewy condition.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] The stability of numerical schemes is closely associated with numerical error.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] A finite difference scheme is stable if the errors made at one time step of the calculation do not cause the errors to be magnified as the computations are continued.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] A *neutrally stable scheme* is one in which errors remain constant as the computations are carried forward.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] If the errors decay and eventually damp out, the numerical scheme is said to be stable.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] If, on the contrary, the errors grow with time the numerical scheme is said to be unstable.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] The stability of numerical schemes can be investigated by performing von Neumann stability analysis.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] For time-dependent problems, stability guarantees that the numerical method produces a bounded solution whenever the solution of the exact differential equation is bounded.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Stability, in general, can be difficult to investigate, especially when the equation under consideration is nonlinear.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Von Neumann stability is necessary in a much wider variety of cases.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] It is often used in place of a more detailed stability analysis to provide a good guess at the restrictions (if any) on the step sizes used in the scheme because of its relative simplicity.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] The von Neumann method is based on the decomposition of the errors into Fourier series.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Then the solution $u_{j}^{n}$ of the discrete equation approximates the analytical solution $u(x,t)$ of the PDE on the grid.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Define the round-off error $\epsilon _{j}^{n}$ as $\epsilon _{j}^{n}=N_{j}^{n}-u_{j}^{n}$ where $u_{j}^{n}$ is the solution of the discretized equation (**1**) that would be computed in the absence of round-off error, and $N_{j}^{n}$ is the numerical solution obtained in finite precision arithmetic.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Since the exact solution $u_{j}^{n}$ must satisfy the discretized equation exactly, the error $\epsilon _{j}^{n}$ must also satisfy the discretized equation.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Here we assumed that $N_{j}^{n}$ satisfies the equation, too (this is only true in machine precision).
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Equations (**1**) and (**2**) show that both the error and the numerical solution have the same growth or decay behavior with respect to time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] The time dependence of the error is included by assuming that the amplitude of error $E_{m}$ is a function of time.
[src:finite-difference-methods/von-neumann-stability-analysis] Often the assumption is made that the error grows or decays exponentially with time, but this is not necessary for the stability analysis.
